---
import { Image } from 'astro:assets';
import prototrak from '../../assets/field/prototrak.png';
import drilled from '../../assets/field/drilled.png';
import table from '../../assets/field/table.png';
import truck from '../../assets/field/truck.png';
import fieldbuilt from '../../assets/field/fieldbuilt.png';
import welding from '../../assets/field/welding.png';
import doors from '../../assets/field/doors.png';
import powdercoated from '../../assets/field/powdercoated.jpg';
import scouthut from '../../assets/field/scouthut.jpg';
import assembled2 from '../../assets/field/assembled2.jpg';
import ds from '../../assets/field/ds.jpg';
import elementconstruction from '../../assets/field/elementconstruction.jpeg';
import wallfit from '../../assets/field/wallfit.jpeg';
import reef from '../../assets/field/reef.jpeg';
import thumbnail from '../../assets/field/thumbnail.jpeg';
import finalassem from '../../assets/field/finalassem.jpeg';
import reefcad from '../../assets/field/reefcad.png';
import finalintegration from '../../assets/field/finalintegration.png';

---

<div>
  <Image
    class="project-image border  border-black"
    src={prototrak}
    alt="Me operating a prototrak vertical mill"
    densities={[1, 2, 3]} 
  />

  <br/>
  <p class="text-white">
    The first was this Prototrak mill, which has steppers and a conversational interface. I set up a stop and waypoints for each of the holes on the pattern, and since I designed all my 5/16 holes to have a consistent distance from an edge, this single setup was enough to drill all of the tubes over the course of a couple days.
  </p>
  <br/>
  <Image
    class="project-image border  border-black"
    src={drilled}
    alt="Stacks of drilled steel box tube"
    densities={[1, 2, 3]} 
  />
  <br/>
  <p class="text-white">
    This was the first batch of steel tubing after deburring the holes. There were two more of these for the whole field to be completed.
    <br/><br/>
    The next major thing that helped accelerate the fabrication was this crazy Siegmund weld fixturing table. This enabled us to do setups for all the sections and weld directly.
  </p>
  <br/>
  <Image
    class="project-image border  border-black"
    src={table}
    alt="Welding table with setup"
    densities={[1, 2, 3]} 
  />
  <br/>
  <Image
    class="project-image border  border-black"
    src={welding}
    alt="Me welding on the setup table"
    densities={[1, 2, 3]} 
  />
  <br/>
  <p class="text-white">
    After all of this was complete, the doors were welded seperately with some clamps. Bit tedious, but got done quickly.
    <br/>
  </p>
  <br/>
  <Image
    class="project-image border  border-black"
    src={doors}
    alt="doors setup with clamps to be welded"
    densities={[1, 2, 3]} 
  />
  <br/>
  <p class="text-white">
    And yes, it did indeed all fit in the back of the truck once grinded and finished.
    <br/>
  </p>
  <br/>
  <Image
    class="project-image border  border-black"
    src={truck}
    alt="doors setup with clamps to be welded"
    densities={[1, 2, 3]} 
  />
  <br/>
  <Image
    class="project-image border  border-black"
    src={fieldbuilt}
    alt="doors setup with clamps to be welded"
    densities={[1, 2, 3]} 
  />
  <br/>
  <h1 class="mb-4 text-3xl font-extrabold leading-tight text-gray-900 lg:mb-6 lg:text-3xl text-white">
    Next Steps
  </h1>
  <p class="text-white">
    After completing a dry fit of all the parts in the space, they went off to be powdercoated at Leon's in Oakland. When they came back a week later, powdercoated in military beige (the color of free!), they were once again transformed.
    <br/>
    <br/>
  </p>
  <Image
    class="project-image border  border-black"
    src={powdercoated}
    alt="truck bed full of powdercoated sections"
    densities={[1, 2, 3]} 
  />
</br>
  <p class="text-white">
    Having completed all the powdercoating, the polycarbonate was also back from CNCing and everything was ready to integrate. I took it to my Scout Hut (the troop has off time during the holidays) and prepared for final integration. 
    <br/>
    <br/>
  </p>
  <Image
    class="project-image border  border-black"
    src={scouthut}
    alt="stacks of sections and lexan inside scout hut"
    densities={[1, 2, 3]} 
  />
<br/>
  <h1 class="mb-4 text-3xl font-extrabold leading-tight text-gray-900 lg:mb-6 lg:text-3xl text-white">
    Skinning the walls
  </h1>
  <p class="text-white">
    Have any of ya'll ever used self-drilling screws? Well then you know they suck! Though I knew that during the desgin process, I could have never expected what we were in for during the almost 9 hours it took us to integrate everything.

    <br/>
    <br/>
    Working with a team of several people, we ended up having to pre drill all the holes in the steel, using the polycarbonate sections as a drilling template. The sizing here was incredibly precise. 3/16 was too large, and 5/32 too small. Using #10 self-drilling screws, only an 11/64 hole would create a reliable tap. We also used cutting oil, which further helped reduce the chances of snapping the screws.
    <br/>
    <br/>
  </p>
  <Image
  class="project-image border  border-black"
  src={assembled2}
  alt="finished door section with lexan inside scout hut"
  densities={[1, 2, 3]} 
/>
<br/>
  <p class="text-white">
    Finally, we were in. After self-drilling and oiling, everything went smoothly. We also cut and drilled the 3/4 inch plywood for the driver station sections and drilled a 2 3/8 hole for some cable grommets. 
  </p>
<br/>
<Image
  class="project-image border  border-black"
  src={ds}
  alt="finished door section with lexan inside scout hut"
  densities={[1, 2, 3]} 
/>
<br/>
<h1 class="mb-4 text-3xl font-extrabold leading-tight text-gray-900 lg:mb-6 lg:text-3xl text-white">
  Getting it all assembled
</h1>

<p class="text-white">
  With the integrated sections loaded into a truck, we headed over to the final space to assemble the walls and feet, which had just been delivered from Fabworks. Since the game hadn't been released, we weren't quite sure how the field would be oriented.
</p>
<br/>
<Image
  class="project-image border  border-black"
  src={wallfit}
  alt="assembled wall sections laid out in final space"
  densities={[1, 2, 3]} 
/>
<br/>
<p class="text-white">
  Everything fit together perfectly, which meant we were waiting on the field carpet and game release to go any farther. On January 4th, the game came out, and a week later, we laid down the carpet in the space-two halfs taped down the middle with 4-inch gaff tape. That meant field element construction could begin.
  <br/>
  <br/>
  Seeing as I was busy with building 8033's 2025 robot, my efforts shifted mostly to the design and management side as I delegated across a team of ~10 parents and mentors. I designed some of the field elements in Onshape, based off plans from REV robotics, and also got some help from 8033 alum Charlie Lambert, who designed the player stations. The final field element build required almost $5000 dollars worth of plywood, even at an insutrial supplier's best contractor rate. It was truly a project of massive proportions.
</p>
<br/>
<Image
  class="project-image border  border-black"
  src={elementconstruction}
  alt="8033 parents beginning final element construction"
  densities={[1, 2, 3]} 
/>
<br/>
<p class="text-white">
  FIRST threw us a massive curveball with the "reefs," hexagonal elements with bent and welded tubes for game piece scoring. Faced with a limited timeline and the desire to build something robust, I designed a version of the reefs that could be built from plywood and welded box tube, which we then put PVC on top of to make it act like the round-tube ones on the real field.
</p>
<br/>
<div class="image-container">
  <Image
    class="split-image border border-black"
    src={reefcad}
    alt="Image of CAD model of REEF"
    densities={[1, 2, 3]} 
  />
  <Image
    class="split-image border border-black"
    src={reef}
    alt="Image of plywood, steel REEF"
    densities={[1, 2, 3]} 
  />
  
</div>
<br/>
<p class="text-white">
  These two REEF structures absorbed the two poles on our field, which was an incredibly lucky coincedence. After a small amount of fitting work, we ended up with a clean field. Final construction went quickly as we integrated the reefs, perimemeter, driver stations, and massive BARGE structure in the center, designed for robots to hang on at the end of the match.
</p>
<br/>
<Image
    class="project-image border border-black"
    src={finalassem}
    alt="Incomplete field"
    densities={[1, 2, 3]} 
  />
<br/>
<p class="text-white">
  As of last week, the field is complete - and we've been running our Alpha robot there for about 2 weeks now. 
</p>
<br/>
<Image
    class="project-image border border-black"
    src={finalintegration}
    alt="Completed field"
    densities={[1, 2, 3]} 
  />
  <br/>
  <video class="border border-black" autoplay muted loop playsinline>
    <source src="https://x0rnmezct8.ufs.sh/f/R4XuC0BXcUqQ7tRTyGbVL9CYcy6Mfz4T1tjPZsEQGOD8Xm5A" type="video/webm"/>
    </video>
<br/>
<h1 class="mb-4 text-3xl font-extrabold leading-tight text-gray-900 lg:mb-6 lg:text-3xl text-white">
      Conclusion
</h1>
<p class="text-white">
  As we work towards opening our field for use by other teams, I reflect on this endeavor as easily my largest, longest, and most team-driven project. Even with an incredible team of parent and mentor volunteers, from start to finish it took almost 5 months and would have cost over $50,000 without generous sponsorships and discounts. 
  
  <br/>
  <br/>
  At the same time, I believe it was worth it, and I'm super proud of how it came out - especially the little details, like the cable grommets, rubber plugs pressed into the exposed tube ends, steel reef trees, powdercoated feet and precisely located Apriltags. It really appeals to my perfectionism.
  <br/>
  <br/>
  I am incredibly proud to leave 8033 with this field as I complete my last year here. I believe it will continue to serve us and the teams in our area for 10+ years to come. 
  
  If you made it this far, thanks for reading; I hope you enjoyed!
</p>
</div>

<style>
  .project-image {
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
  }

  .image-container {
    display: flex;
    gap: 16px; /* Adjust the gap between images if needed */
  }

  .split-image {
    width: 100%;
    max-width: 50%; /* Adjust as needed to control individual image size */
    height: auto;
  }
</style>
